[ENHANCEMENT]
for generic
[ux vx wx tx]
[uy vy wy ty]
[uz vz wz tz]
[ 0  0  0  1 ]
matrices with common rot/trans/scaling components, an optimized formula can still be derived, both for det and inv:

``` java
public float det () {
return ( val[M30] == 0 && val[M31] == 0 && val[M32] == 0 && val[M33] == 1 ) ? det3x3() : detGeneric();
}
public float det3x3() { // common OpenGL matrix
        return val[M00] * ( val[M11] * val[M22] - val[M21] * val[M12] )
                + val[M01] * ( val[M12] * val[M20] - val[M10] * val[M22] )
                + val[M02] * ( val[M10] * val[M21] - val[M20] * val[M11] );
    }

    public Matrix4 inv() {
return ( val[M30] == 0 && val[M31] == 0 && val[M32] == 0 && val[M33] == 1 ) ? invRST() : invGeneric();
}

    private Matrix4 invRST() {
        float t00_11 = val[M00] * val[M11],
                t00_12 = val[M00] * val[M12],
                t01_10 = val[M01] * val[M10],
                t01_12 = val[M01] * val[M12],
                t02_10 = val[M02] * val[M10],
                t02_11 = val[M02] * val[M11];

        float det = val[M20] * ( t01_12 - t02_11 )
                + val[M21] * ( t02_10 - t00_12 )
                + val[M22] * ( t00_11 - t01_10 );
        if ( det == 0f ) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException( "det() = 0, non-invertible matrix" );
        }
        float inv_det = 1.0f / det;

        tmp[M00] = val[M11] * val[M22] - val[M12] * val[M21];
        tmp[M01] = val[M02] * val[M21] - val[M01] * val[M22];
        tmp[M02] = t01_12 - t02_11;

        tmp[M10] = val[M12] * val[M20] - val[M10] * val[M22];
        tmp[M11] = val[M00] * val[M22] - val[M02] * val[M20];
        tmp[M12] = t02_10 - t00_12;

        tmp[M20] = val[M10] * val[M21] - val[M11] * val[M20];
        tmp[M21] = val[M01] * val[M20] - val[M00] * val[M21];
        tmp[M22] = t00_11 - t01_10;

        tmp[M30] = -( val[M30] * tmp[M00]
                + val[M31] * tmp[M10]
                + val[M32] * tmp[M20] );
        tmp[M31] = -( val[M30] * tmp[M01]
                + val[M31] * tmp[M11]
                + val[M32] * tmp[M21] );
        tmp[M32] = -( val[M30] * tmp[M02]
                + val[M31] * tmp[M12]
                + val[M32] * tmp[M22] );

        val[M00] = tmp[M00] * inv_det;
        val[M01] = tmp[M01] * inv_det;
        val[M02] = tmp[M02] * inv_det;

        val[M10] = tmp[M10] * inv_det;
        val[M11] = tmp[M11] * inv_det;
        val[M12] = tmp[M12] * inv_det;

        val[M20] = tmp[M20] * inv_det;
        val[M21] = tmp[M21] * inv_det;
        val[M22] = tmp[M22] * inv_det;

        val[M30] = tmp[M30] * inv_det;
        val[M31] = tmp[M31] * inv_det;
        val[M32] = tmp[M32] * inv_det;

        return this;
    }
```

And yeah, those are minor dets there, BTW.

Also, there's a better generic algo, using caching of some of the multiplications for the general case [i.e. "old", generic inv()] - this exact c# code was stolen from http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2624422/efficient-4x4-matrix-inverse-affine-transform, but I use almost identical code myself in my codebase

```
public static double[,] GetInverse(double[,] a)
{
var s0 = a[0, 0] * a[1, 1] - a[1, 0] * a[0, 1];
var s1 = a[0, 0] * a[1, 2] - a[1, 0] * a[0, 2];
var s2 = a[0, 0] * a[1, 3] - a[1, 0] * a[0, 3];
var s3 = a[0, 1] * a[1, 2] - a[1, 1] * a[0, 2];
var s4 = a[0, 1] * a[1, 3] - a[1, 1] * a[0, 3];
var s5 = a[0, 2] * a[1, 3] - a[1, 2] * a[0, 3];

var c5 = a[2, 2] * a[3, 3] - a[3, 2] * a[2, 3];
var c4 = a[2, 1] * a[3, 3] - a[3, 1] * a[2, 3];
var c3 = a[2, 1] * a[3, 2] - a[3, 1] * a[2, 2];
var c2 = a[2, 0] * a[3, 3] - a[3, 0] * a[2, 3];
var c1 = a[2, 0] * a[3, 2] - a[3, 0] * a[2, 2];
var c0 = a[2, 0] * a[3, 1] - a[3, 0] * a[2, 1];

// Should check for 0 determinant
var invdet = 1.0 / (s0 * c5 - s1 * c4 + s2 * c3 + s3 * c2 - s4 * c1 + s5 * c0);

var b = new double[4, 4];

b[0, 0] = ( a[1, 1] * c5 - a[1, 2] * c4 + a[1, 3] * c3) * invdet;
b[0, 1] = (-a[0, 1] * c5 + a[0, 2] * c4 - a[0, 3] * c3) * invdet;
b[0, 2] = ( a[3, 1] * s5 - a[3, 2] * s4 + a[3, 3] * s3) * invdet;
b[0, 3] = (-a[2, 1] * s5 + a[2, 2] * s4 - a[2, 3] * s3) * invdet;

b[1, 0] = (-a[1, 0] * c5 + a[1, 2] * c2 - a[1, 3] * c1) * invdet;
b[1, 1] = ( a[0, 0] * c5 - a[0, 2] * c2 + a[0, 3] * c1) * invdet;
b[1, 2] = (-a[3, 0] * s5 + a[3, 2] * s2 - a[3, 3] * s1) * invdet;
b[1, 3] = ( a[2, 0] * s5 - a[2, 2] * s2 + a[2, 3] * s1) * invdet;

b[2, 0] = ( a[1, 0] * c4 - a[1, 1] * c2 + a[1, 3] * c0) * invdet;
b[2, 1] = (-a[0, 0] * c4 + a[0, 1] * c2 - a[0, 3] * c0) * invdet;
b[2, 2] = ( a[3, 0] * s4 - a[3, 1] * s2 + a[3, 3] * s0) * invdet;
b[2, 3] = (-a[2, 0] * s4 + a[2, 1] * s2 - a[2, 3] * s0) * invdet;

b[3, 0] = (-a[1, 0] * c3 + a[1, 1] * c1 - a[1, 2] * c0) * invdet;
b[3, 1] = ( a[0, 0] * c3 - a[0, 1] * c1 + a[0, 2] * c0) * invdet;
b[3, 2] = (-a[3, 0] * s3 + a[3, 1] * s1 - a[3, 2] * s0) * invdet;
b[3, 3] = ( a[2, 0] * s3 - a[2, 1] * s1 + a[2, 2] * s0) * invdet;

return b;
}
```

Using those codes leads up to about 2-5 faster det/inv calculations. detGeneric() (i.e. the old one) can be cleaned similarily too.

Looking how newest MESA does it, it strikes me as very similar - the only this is that they store flags to know if they can skip some of the calculations ; http://cgit.freedesktop.org/mesa/mesa/tree/src/mesa/math/m_matrix.c?h=10.0  - still, even without flags we can make the code much more efficient, as shown above.

What do you think, guys? Should we bother with making `Matrix4` faster? Should I bother with crafting a PR for this?

Hello, I spent a lot of time on optimizing my game and I have one point I want to say/discuss as an potential issue possible to be upgraded.

It's not a breaking news when I'll say that every additional tileLayer influences the performance pretty highly. In my game (15x10) tiles on the screen, sized (64x64 px) with culling (default implementation) rendering tiled map takes 15% of whole game where's a lot of box2d, actors, animations etc. I have only 3 tile layers but for sure I'm gonna need 2 more. With 9 layers it's more than 1/4 of total game. The worst thing is that it's even not rendered because most of them are mainly empty for testing purposes.

I had a feeling that it can be upgraded and it seems that this is the bottleneck:
    <code>
public Cell getCell (int x, int y) {
        if (x < 0 || x >= width) return null;
        if (y < 0 || y >= height) return null;
        return cells[x][y];
    }
</code>
in TiledMapTileLayer. This method is being called for every tile visible on the screen for all 3 layers.so It gives 15x10x3=450 calls per frame in my case. The cell array is pretty big because the level is big. 

I think that making this array cells[y][x] should make a small improvement because most screens are wide and it's better to have 10 arrays of 15 elements than 15 arrays of 10 elements. Or it will be good to have an option to choose if our game is vertical or horizontal. 

Also it is worth to consider if we read the array in the most efficent way (in the order how it's stored in memory) and if the cells are stored in the same order how we want to read them. This is more complicated case because it may be stored in different ways on different devices (iOS i.e) but in Java there are arrays of arrays where elements of one array are continous.

Finally, reading from such big 2d array may be a problem itself. In my case there's a 500x40 tiled map. It's not a big deal but for 995 calls i got 1142 CPU time (DDMS) so it gives ~1ms per call. I use Motorola Moto G with quad core processor 1,2GHz so imagine how it can influence older devices. I think that some kind of partitioning may help if previous ones can't.

What do you think guys about it?

PS getCell is about 60% of whole tiledmap render(). About 30% is the method itself. I didn't measure times for every lines but there is a lot of other work implemented there so I don't think that there's any bottleneck. Worth to check though.
